  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal (or \"clean\"). It is a serious financial crime that is illegal in virtually every country around the world.\n\nGovernments and international organizations have established stringent laws and regulations to combat money laundering. These laws are designed to prevent criminals from disguising the origins of their illicit funds and integrating them into the legitimate financial system. Key legislative frameworks and international agreements targeting money laundering include:\n\n1. **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**: This intergovernmental body sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. FATF's recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n\n2. **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: This was one of the first international treaties to address money laundering, specifically in the context of drug trafficking.\n\n3. **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: This convention includes measures to combat money laundering related to organized crime.\n\n4. **The USA PATRIOT Act (2001)**: In the United States, this Act includes provisions to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n5. **The European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**: The EU has issued several directives aimed at preventing money laundering and terrorist financing within its member states.\n\nIn addition to these international and regional frameworks, most countries have their own national laws and regulatory bodies dedicated to combating money laundering. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\nOverall, the global community recognizes money laundering as a significant threat to financial systems, economic stability, and security, and there is a concerted effort to enforce laws and regulations to prevent it.",
